# {{PROJECT_NAME}} (SmartWorkers workspace)

> Generated by `workspace-setup` v{{WORKSPACE_SETUP_VERSION}}.

This folder is set up to help an AI agent (e.g. Codex) do real work in a predictable way, with outputs that are easy to review and share.

## What this workspace is for

Use this workspace when you want an AI agent to complete tasks like:

- Sales/admin: outreach drafts, call summaries, account research
- Recruiting: role briefs, interview kits, candidate comparisons
- Operations: reports, SOP drafts, FAQ/support macros
- Creative: ad copy variants, briefs, outlines, image generation runs
- Software: small scripts, data processing, automation helpers

## Where work goes

- `logs/` — scratch work (drafts, logs, intermediate files). Safe to delete.
- `temp/` — temporary files the user wants to keep around during the work.
- `artifacts/` — final deliverables you can review and share.
- `skills/` — the local source tree for skills created or improved in this workspace.

Tip: each agent run should create matching folders under both:
`logs/<task>/<run-id>/` and `artifacts/<task>/<run-id>/`.
Use `temp/` for user-managed one-off files that do not need the structured run-folder layout.

## Secrets and configuration (important)

- Copy `workers.example.jsonc` to `workers.jsonc`.
- Put API keys and private settings in `workers.jsonc` only.
- Do not commit `workers.jsonc` to git (it should be ignored automatically).

## Tools and skill setup

This workspace is not fully set up until the required skill baseline is in place: `mise` runtimes for the machine, the global `skills` npm package, plus the Codex skills `skill-creator` and `smart-skill-maker`. Keep workspace-local authored skill sources under `skills/`, and use `npx skills ...` to install or refresh Codex skills from this workspace.

```sh
mise use -g node@24 python@3.14 uv@latest
# Install/apply Codex skills from the workspace root:
npx skills ...
```

- `npx skills ...` is the only tool for installing or updating Codex skills for this workspace.
- `skill-creator` and `smart-skill-maker` are required parts of the workspace setup baseline, not optional add-ons.
- Use `smart-skill-maker` as the only tool for creating or improving skills in this workspace.
- Keep authored source skills inside the workspace-local `skills/` tree, then apply them to Codex with `npx skills ...`.
- Do not use `skill-installer` or manual copying for workspace skills.
- Keep skill names stable and use frontmatter `metadata.skill_version` to distinguish revisions.
- Increment `metadata.skill_version` every time a skill is updated.
- If a task later needs helper scripts or extra tooling, prefer mature, well-known tools before writing custom one-off code.
- Good examples:
  - `ffmpeg` for video/audio conversion or extraction
  - `ImageMagick` for image conversion, compositing, and batch processing
  - `uv` for Python environments and dependency sync
  - repo-local `npm` scripts for Node workflows
- Avoid random community utilities unless a technical teammate has approved them for this workspace.

If a task needs a tool that is not installed yet, ask the agent or a technical teammate to install the established tool rather than building a fragile replacement from scratch.

## How to use with Codex

1) Open Codex in this folder.
2) Update `WORKFLOW.md` when you have recurring ways of working you want the agent to follow.
3) Say `work work` when you want Codex to consult `WORKFLOW.md` before starting.
4) If setup was deferred earlier, finish the required skill bootstrap before relying on workspace skills.
5) Use `npx skills ...` to install or refresh Codex skills from this workspace.
6) Keep locally authored skill sources under `skills/`, then apply them to Codex with `npx skills ...`.
7) Use `smart-skill-maker` when you want to create or improve a skill.
8) Ask for a task and specify outputs, for example:

> Output: write drafts to `logs/<task>/<run-id>/` and final deliverables to `artifacts/<task>/<run-id>/`.

See `AGENTS.md` for the detailed rules the agent follows.
